{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641023"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17857"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17857"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0,0.83,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10571"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24650"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas is the primary producer of lipase, a digestive enzyme responsible for breaking down fats in food to allow for absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the primary site where pancreatic lipase acts to digest dietary fats?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreas","Stomach","Small intestine","Large intestine","Mouth"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELipase is released into the duodenum, where the \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall intestine \u003C/strong\u003Ebegins, breaking down triglycerides into free fatty acids and monoglycerides, facilitating absorption by the intestinal lining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E is the organ that produces pancreatic lipase, but the enzyme does not perform its digestive function there.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estomach\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the initial digestion of proteins and some fats, but the acidic environment is not conducive for the action of pancreatic lipase and anatomically, this is not feasible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge intestine\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in the absorption of water and electrolytes, and does not play a significant role in fat digestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emouth\u003C/strong\u003E is where digestion begins, with enzymes like salivary amylase starting the breakdown of carbohydrates, but it is not the site of action for pancreatic lipase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic lipase is essential for the digestion of dietary fats in the small intestine.","The enzyme is secreted by the pancreas and becomes active in the small intestine.","The small intestine is the primary site for the digestion and absorption of nutrients."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"